>thank you for the advice.
I'd rather actually give advice than be thanked for advice when all I did was complain about something, so here.
The key to good reptilian tails is understanding that they're a extension of the torso, so the word of the day with them is always flow.
Here I tried to have the tail rest on top of the box, which made it a touch more scrunched up then I'd of liked. There's also the point too that crocodilians use their tails to swim, so they're very rudder like in shape, especially closer to the tail tip. This doesn't translate well to a simple redline, but I tried to show that it doesn't really come to a fine taper like it does originally. It could be depicted slightly shorter then I had it here now I look at it, but that's more to personal preference.

Anonymous Wed 27 May 2020 17:16:16 No.30521008 Report
Quoted By:
>>30520786
>It seems like it would be the same for sharks or anything with such a wide tail base.
Basically, yeah. The key difference between something like a dog or giraffe tail vs a tail on a dragon or a fish, is with the former, they still have muscles and tendons and bones, but they're so small that they can get away with a tail that only connects to the rest of the body from a very small attach point.
With the latter, where the tail IS part of the torso, there's so much more mass that mechanically speaking you can't reasonably have all that muscle and other flesh hang off of a small point, so thus it has to be integrated and anchored onto the rest of the body to make sense.
>Wouldn't that remove a good portion of butt though?
Yep, there's no way around it, and that's the reason why so many artists actively don't have proper tails on their lizards and other similar animals. To have a proper tail basically entirely absorbs the glutes, unless the hips are so wide that this is negated to some degree, and even then it becomes difficult to find a balance without sacrificing either butt volume or the tail size or being mounted right. The place with the biggest amount of reference of this being done right is with (non-furry) art of theropods, your raptors and T-rex's and things. Not quite exactly the same as you have to imagine then with their torso upright, and the crotch can be made narrower than your average dinosaur to retain something closer to anthropomorphic, but they still show the general construction well.
